<div class="section">
  <p class="text-heading-2">Studying the Current Landscape</p>
  <p class="text-body">I wanted to better understand the <strong>product’s evolution and vision</strong>, and started by reviewing prior work done on desktop. Conveniently, the lead designer on this turned out to be my mentor, whom I happily pestered relentlessly. Conducting an <strong>audit of analogous tools helped me identify common features and interactions to gain inspiration and benchmark the product.</strong></p>
  <div class="subsection w-full">
    <img src="/images/deshaw_existingtools.png"/>
  </div>
  <div class="subsection w-full md:w-1/2">
    <img src="/images/deshaw_comparativeanalysis.webp"/>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <p class="text-heading-2">Speaking to Stakeholders</p>
  <p class="text-heading-3"> 14 Stakeholders | 6 Business Units | 6 Semi-Structured Interviews </p>
  <p class="text-body"> I conducted virtual interviews to better understand <strong>Firm-specific requirements.</strong> I met with key stakeholders: including people from UX, the dev team, and multiple business units who’d be using the product. The user groups I was targetting were VERY busy; <strong>exhaustive interviews weren’t possible.</strong> To optimise my use of their time, I realised focusing on goal-oriented, open-ended ‘why’ questions yielded richer answers than did feature-based ‘what’ questions. </p>
  <p class="text-body"> After these quick user studies, I had to analyse the data to fill in the gaps. Here, putting myself in the user’s shoes and <strong>laying out a scenario</strong> in the form of a (wholly fictional and assumptive) story helped me open the project to a breadth of possibilities. </p>
  <p class="text-body"> Post affinitising insights, I realised <strong>use-cases fell into 3 main categories.</strong> </p>
  <div class="subsection w-full">
    <img src="/images/deshaw_usecases.webp"/>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <p class="text-heading-2">Whom will this benefit?</p>
  <p class="text-heading-3">Defining High-Level Stakeholders</p>
  <p class="text-body"> <strong>To streamline the design process and create a consistent interface for discussion,</strong> I generated proto-personas. This was challenging and assumptive. So I kept reverting to and refining this data visualisation, and made sure to document my decisions.</p>
  <div class="subsection w-full">
    <img src="/images/deshaw_personas.webp"/>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <p class="text-heading-2">Generating ideas</p>
  <p class="text-heading-3">Six thinking hats | Mind-mapping | Collective brainstorming (rapid ideation)</p>
  <p class="text-body">I was excited to try out the 6-Thinking Hats method, which allows for parallel styles of thinking: logic, emotion, caution, optimism, creativity, and control, ensuring a holistic coverage of perspectives. After several rapid ideation sessions (including one with other members of the team), I created a mind-map.</p>
  <div class="pt-12">
    <a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1g0zIT4ecbQZrHVdp34NCVr-FfQbpjY_b/view" class="button">6 Thinking hats</a>
  </div>
  <p class="text-body pt-6">I started visualizing my ideas to better validate them, through several <strong>quick-and-dirty paper prototypes.</strong></p>
  <div class="subsection w-full md:w-1/2">
    <img src="/images/deshaw_lowfi.webp"/>
  </div>
  <p class="text-body pt-6">After exploring the wild breadth of possible solutions, I promptly got thoroughly confused and overwhelmed about the project scope. So <strong>I presented these concepts to the team to gather feedback, and determine next steps.</strong>​ At the time, I was also impatient to quickly narrow down the list of possibilities, so I could stay on schedule and iterate through a few rounds of prototypes. In retrospect, I think that as an intern, my lack of experience was a concern (although a known devil). One key thing the team was likely looking for was the attitude and enthusiasm — and fresh ideas — brought to the table. Also, an unexpected realisation was that a wide base of divergent content can be crucial for me to narrow down effectively — as there’s no lingering ‘itch’ of what-if.</p>
</div>


